<font color="#FF0000">DEALING WITH PTSD</font><br>
<tt>Fri Jan 16 12:31:27 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
Now that my father is nearly fifty years old, he is ready to admit to his family and himself that he suffers PTSD, and that there is no shame in it.  Together we are working on a book to sort out the way VN has shaped him as a person and parent, and how it has shaped the way I see the world.  I think that somewhere between their midlife crises and their imminent deaths, VN vets carrying this weight need to find a way to begin to let it go.  We are compiling an anthology of anecdotes (both positive and negative) by both VN veterans and their children about how they did (or, in my case, didn't) come to terms with the scarring legacy of Vietnam, the penultimate paradigm shift of the twentieth century.  You don't need to be an author to contribute, just someone who has has gained insight and some kernel of truth gathered by result of involvement in Vietnam.  E-mail us for guidelines.  We wish you peace, solace and self-forgiveness.<br>
 
<p><code>-- jcolella@wam.umd.edu  (James and Jill Colella) </code><p>


